1
00:02:43,997 --> 00:02:46,959
The hills are alive

2
00:02:47,000 --> 00:02:51,255
With the sound of music

3
00:02:51,755 --> 00:02:54,216
With songs they have sung

4
00:02:54,258 --> 00:02:58,929
For a thousand years

5
00:02:59,513 --> 00:03:02,766
The hills fill my heart

6
00:03:02,808 --> 00:03:07,229
With the sound of music

7
00:03:07,771 --> 00:03:14,444
My heart wants to sing
Every song it hears

8
00:03:15,404 --> 00:03:20,450
My heart wants to beat like the wings
Of the birds that rise

9
00:03:20,492 --> 00:03:23,453
From the lake to the trees

10
00:03:23,954 --> 00:03:28,292
My heart wants to sigh
Like a chime that flies

11
00:03:28,333 --> 00:03:32,171
From a church on a breeze

12
00:03:32,713 --> 00:03:36,258
To laugh like a brook
When it trips and falls

13
00:03:36,300 --> 00:03:39,636
Over stones on its way

14
00:03:40,137 --> 00:03:43,932
To sing through the night

15
00:03:43,974 --> 00:03:48,187
Like a lark who is learning to pray

16
00:03:48,228 --> 00:03:53,609
I go to the hills

17
00:03:54,276 --> 00:04:00,115
When my heart is lonely

18
00:04:00,657 --> 00:04:03,744
I know I will hear

19
00:04:03,785 --> 00:04:09,082
What I've heard before

20
00:04:09,583 --> 00:04:13,504
My heart will be blessed

21
00:04:14,463 --> 00:04:21,386
With the sound of music

22
00:04:23,347 --> 00:04:28,352
And I'll sing

23
00:04:28,644 --> 00:04:35,484
Once more

24
00:09:19,601 --> 00:09:24,314
Hallelujah, hallelujah

25
00:09:24,565 --> 00:09:29,486
Hallelujah, hallelujah

26
00:09:31,864 --> 00:09:34,074
-Reverend Mother.
-Sister Bernice.

27
00:09:34,116 --> 00:09:36,910
-I simply cannot find her.
-Maria?

28
00:09:37,953 --> 00:09:39,955
She's missing again.

29
00:09:39,997 --> 00:09:42,624
We should've put a cowbell
around her neck.

30
00:09:42,666 --> 00:09:45,961
Have you tried the barn? You know
how much she adores the animals.

31
00:09:46,003 --> 00:09:48,922
I have looked everywhere.
In all of the usual places.

32
00:09:48,964 --> 00:09:51,425
Sister, considering it's Maria,

33
00:09:51,466 --> 00:09:54,428
I suggest you look in
someplace unusual.

34
00:09:59,349 --> 00:10:00,809
Well, Reverend Mother,

35
00:10:00,851 --> 00:10:03,729
I hope this new infraction ends
whatever doubts

36
00:10:03,770 --> 00:10:07,149
you may still have
about Maria's future here.

37
00:10:07,191 --> 00:10:11,278
I always try to keep faith
in my doubts, Sister Berthe.

38
00:10:11,528 --> 00:10:14,615
After all, the wool of a black sheep
is just as warm.

39
00:10:14,656 --> 00:10:18,952
We are not talking about sheep,
black or white, Sister Margaretta.

40
00:10:19,203 --> 00:10:22,956
Of all the candidates for
the novitiate, Maria is the least...

41
00:10:22,998 --> 00:10:24,750
Children, children.

42
00:10:25,876 --> 00:10:29,838
We were speculating about
the qualifications of our postulants.

43
00:10:30,464 --> 00:10:33,467
The Mistress of Novices
and the Mistress of Postulants

44
00:10:33,717 --> 00:10:38,597
were trying to help me
by expressing opposite points of view.

45
00:10:39,223 --> 00:10:42,684
Tell me, Sister Catherine,
what do you think of Maria?

46
00:10:42,726 --> 00:10:45,395
She's a wonderful girl,
some of the time.

47
00:10:46,688 --> 00:10:49,858
-Sister Agatha?
-It's very easy to like Maria,

48
00:10:49,900 --> 00:10:52,152
except when it's difficult.

49
00:10:52,694 --> 00:10:56,365
-And you, Sister Sophia?
-Oh, I love her very dearly.

50
00:10:56,406 --> 00:10:59,618
But she always seems to be
in trouble, doesn't she?

51
00:10:59,660 --> 00:11:01,703
Exactly what I say.

52
00:11:01,745 --> 00:11:04,289
She climbs a tree and scrapes her knee

53
00:11:04,331 --> 00:11:06,750
Her dress has got a tear

54
00:11:06,792 --> 00:11:11,547
She waltzes on her way to Mass
And whistles on the stair

55
00:11:11,588 --> 00:11:16,301
And underneath her wimple
She has curlers in her hair

56
00:11:16,343 --> 00:11:20,931
I've even heard her singing
In the abbey

57
00:11:21,181 --> 00:11:23,225
She's always late for chapel

58
00:11:23,267 --> 00:11:25,894
But her penitence is real

59
00:11:25,936 --> 00:11:28,272
She's always late for everything

60
00:11:28,522 --> 00:11:30,566
Except for every meal

61
00:11:30,816 --> 00:11:35,571
I hate to have to say it
But I very firmly feel

62
00:11:35,946 --> 00:11:40,826
Maria's not an asset to the abbey

63
00:11:40,868 --> 00:11:43,537
I'd like to say a word in her behalf

64
00:11:43,579 --> 00:11:45,747
Say it, Sister Margaretta.

65
00:11:45,789 --> 00:11:49,209
Maria makes me laugh

66
00:11:52,713 --> 00:11:55,924
How do you solve a problem like Maria?

67
00:11:56,884 --> 00:12:00,387
How do you catch a cloud
And pin it down?

68
00:12:00,888 --> 00:12:04,266
How do you find a word
That means Maria?

69
00:12:04,766 --> 00:12:05,767
A flibbertigibbet

70
00:12:05,809 --> 00:12:07,936
-A will-o'-the-wisp
-A clown

71
00:12:09,146 --> 00:12:12,482
Many a thing you know
You'd like to tell her

72
00:12:13,025 --> 00:12:16,653
Many a thing she ought to understand

73
00:12:16,987 --> 00:12:21,283
But how do you make her stay
And listen to all you say?

74
00:12:21,325 --> 00:12:24,745
How do you keep a wave
Upon the sand?

75
00:12:25,495 --> 00:12:29,541
How do you solve a problem like Maria?

76
00:12:29,583 --> 00:12:34,796
How do you hold a moonbeam

77
00:12:35,339 --> 00:12:40,802
In your hand?

78
00:12:41,929 --> 00:12:45,599
When I'm with her I'm confused
Out of focus and bemused

79
00:12:45,641 --> 00:12:49,269
And I never know exactly where I am

80
00:12:49,311 --> 00:12:52,814
-Unpredictable as weather
-She's as flighty as a feather

81
00:12:52,856 --> 00:12:54,858
-She's a darling
-She's a demon

82
00:12:54,900 --> 00:12:56,485
She's a lamb

83
00:12:56,777 --> 00:13:00,614
She'll out pester any pest
Drive a hornet from its nest

84
00:13:00,656 --> 00:13:03,951
She can throw a whirling dervish
Out of whirl

85
00:13:04,535 --> 00:13:08,497
-She is gentle, she is wild
-She's a riddle, she's a child

86
00:13:08,539 --> 00:13:11,333
-She's a headache
-She's an angel

87
00:13:11,375 --> 00:13:15,295
She's a girl

88
00:13:16,171 --> 00:13:19,800
How do you solve a problem like Maria?

89
00:13:20,175 --> 00:13:23,846
How do you catch a cloud
And pin it down?

90
00:13:24,179 --> 00:13:27,724
How do you find a word
That means Maria?

91
00:13:27,975 --> 00:13:30,143
-A flibbertigibbet
-A will-o'-the-wisp

92
00:13:30,185 --> 00:13:31,854
A clown

93
00:13:32,229 --> 00:13:35,899
Many a thing you know
You'd like to tell her

94
00:13:36,400 --> 00:13:39,736
Many a thing she ought to understand

95
00:13:40,195 --> 00:13:44,533
-But how do you make her stay?
-And listen to all you say?

96
00:13:44,575 --> 00:13:48,412
How do you keep a wave
Upon the sand?

97
00:13:48,912 --> 00:13:54,251
How do you solve a problem like Maria?

98
00:14:10,684 --> 00:14:17,149
How do you hold a moonbeam

99
00:14:18,442 --> 00:14:24,781
in your hand?

100
00:14:36,585 --> 00:14:38,587
You may go in now, Maria.

101
00:14:51,141 --> 00:14:52,976
Come here, my child.

102
00:14:59,316 --> 00:15:00,817
Now sit down.

103
00:15:01,818 --> 00:15:05,405
Reverend Mother, I'm sorry.
I couldn't help myself.

104
00:15:05,447 --> 00:15:08,492
-The hills were beckoning and before...
-Dear.

105
00:15:08,909 --> 00:15:10,869
I haven't summoned you for apologies.

106
00:15:10,911 --> 00:15:13,413
Please let me ask for forgiveness.

107
00:15:13,997 --> 00:15:16,041
If you'll feel better.

108
00:15:16,083 --> 00:15:18,710
Yes, you see,
the sky was so blue today

109
00:15:18,752 --> 00:15:22,714
and everything was so green and
fragrant, I had to be a part of it.

110
00:15:22,756 --> 00:15:27,427
The Untersberg led me higher like
it wanted me to go through the clouds.

111
00:15:27,469 --> 00:15:29,930
Suppose darkness had come
and you were lost?

112
00:15:29,972 --> 00:15:32,224
Mother, I could never be lost
up there.

113
00:15:32,266 --> 00:15:35,310
That's my mountain.
I was brought up on it.

114
00:15:35,352 --> 00:15:37,855
It was the mountain that
led me to you.

115
00:15:38,480 --> 00:15:41,567
When I was a child,
I would come down and climb a tree

116
00:15:41,608 --> 00:15:43,569
and look in your garden.

117
00:15:43,610 --> 00:15:46,864
I'd see the sisters at work
and hear them sing.

118
00:15:47,990 --> 00:15:51,827
Which brings me to another
transgression, Reverend Mother.

119
00:15:51,869 --> 00:15:54,162
I was singing out there today.

120
00:15:54,705 --> 00:15:58,625
Only in the abbey do we have rules
about postulants singing.

121
00:15:58,667 --> 00:16:01,170
I can't stop wherever I am.

122
00:16:01,211 --> 00:16:03,714
Worse, I can't seem to stop
saying things.

123
00:16:03,755 --> 00:16:06,175
Everything I think and feel.

124
00:16:06,216 --> 00:16:07,759
Some call that "honesty."

125
00:16:07,801 --> 00:16:10,179
Oh, but it's terrible,
Reverend Mother!

126
00:16:10,554 --> 00:16:14,725
You know how Sister Berthe makes me
kiss the floor after a disagreement?

127
00:16:14,766 --> 00:16:18,729
Lately, I kiss the floor
when I see her coming to save time.

128
00:16:20,898 --> 00:16:22,065
Maria,

129
00:16:23,025 --> 00:16:26,361
when you saw us over the wall
and longed to be with us,

130
00:16:26,403 --> 00:16:31,116
that didn't mean you were prepared
for the way we live here, did it?

131
00:16:32,409 --> 00:16:34,870
No, Mother, but I pray and I try.

132
00:16:34,912 --> 00:16:37,039
And I am learning. I really am.

133
00:16:37,080 --> 00:16:40,209
What is the most important lesson
you have learned here?

134
00:16:40,250 --> 00:16:44,046
To find out what is the will of God
and do it wholeheartedly.

135
00:16:46,882 --> 00:16:48,008
Maria,

136
00:16:49,510 --> 00:16:52,638
it seems to be God's will
that you leave us.

137
00:16:52,679 --> 00:16:54,681
-Leave?
-Only for a while.

138
00:16:54,723 --> 00:16:57,267
No, Mother!
Please don't send me away!

139
00:16:57,309 --> 00:17:01,605
This is where I belong. It's my home,
my family. It's my life.

140
00:17:02,189 --> 00:17:05,150
-Are you truly ready for it?
-Yes, I am.

141
00:17:05,192 --> 00:17:10,113
If you go out into the world for a time,
knowing what we expect of you,

142
00:17:10,614 --> 00:17:13,367
you will find out
if you can expect it of yourself.

143
00:17:13,407 --> 00:17:16,703
I know what you expect, Mother,
and I can do it! I promise I can!

144
00:17:16,744 --> 00:17:17,871
Maria.

145
00:17:21,250 --> 00:17:22,459
Yes, Mother.

146
00:17:24,711 --> 00:17:26,380
If it is God's will.

147
00:17:28,590 --> 00:17:33,470
There is a family near Salzburg that
needs a governess until September.

148
00:17:33,846 --> 00:17:36,265
-September?
-For seven children.

149
00:17:36,890 --> 00:17:38,100
Seven children?

150
00:17:38,141 --> 00:17:40,018
Do you like children?

151
00:17:40,060 --> 00:17:41,854
Well, yes, but seven!

152
00:17:43,105 --> 00:17:46,483
I will tell Captain von Trapp
to expect you tomorrow.

153
00:17:47,359 --> 00:17:48,694
Captain?

154
00:17:49,278 --> 00:17:53,949
A retired officer of the Imperial Navy.
A fine man and a brave one.

155
00:17:53,991 --> 00:17:56,743
His wife died,
and he is alone with the children.

156
00:17:56,785 --> 00:18:01,081
I understand he has had a difficult time
keeping a governess there.

157
00:18:02,833 --> 00:18:05,127
Why difficult, Reverend Mother?

158
00:18:05,919 --> 00:18:08,839
The Lord will show you
in his own good time.

159
00:18:45,417 --> 00:18:48,128
When the Lord closes a door,

160
00:18:48,170 --> 00:18:50,672
somewhere he opens a window.

161
00:18:52,883 --> 00:18:56,678
What will this day be like?

162
00:18:58,096 --> 00:18:59,932
I wonder

163
00:19:06,897 --> 00:19:10,817
What will my future be?

164
00:19:11,818 --> 00:19:13,946
I wonder

165
00:19:15,739 --> 00:19:18,825
It could be so exciting

166
00:19:18,867 --> 00:19:22,162
To be out in the world
To be free

167
00:19:22,204 --> 00:19:25,624
My heart should be wildly rejoicing

168
00:19:26,583 --> 00:19:31,713
Oh, what's the matter with me?

169
00:19:32,005 --> 00:19:35,467
I've always longed for adventure

170
00:19:35,509 --> 00:19:39,263
To do the things I've never dared

171
00:19:39,304 --> 00:19:42,432
Now here I'm facing adventure

172
00:19:42,850 --> 00:19:48,897
Then why am I so scared?

173
00:19:52,359 --> 00:19:54,611
A captain with seven children

174
00:19:55,571 --> 00:19:57,865
What's so fearsome about that?

175
00:20:00,534 --> 00:20:03,579
I must stop these doubts
All these worries

176
00:20:03,620 --> 00:20:06,748
If I don't, I just know I'll turn back

177
00:20:06,790 --> 00:20:10,335
I must dream of the things
I am seeking

178
00:20:11,253 --> 00:20:15,799
I am seeking the courage I lack

179
00:20:16,967 --> 00:20:20,220
The courage to serve them
With reliance

180
00:20:21,054 --> 00:20:23,849
Face my mistakes without defiance

181
00:20:24,308 --> 00:20:26,101
Show them I'm worthy

182
00:20:26,143 --> 00:20:29,062
And while I show them

183
00:20:29,104 --> 00:20:33,317
I'll show me

184
00:20:33,358 --> 00:20:38,780
So let them bring on
All their problems

185
00:20:38,822 --> 00:20:41,825
I'll do better than my best

186
00:20:42,326 --> 00:20:45,662
I have confidence
They'll put me to the test

187
00:20:45,704 --> 00:20:49,291
But I'll make them see
I have confidence in me

188
00:20:49,333 --> 00:20:52,794
Somehow, I will impress them

189
00:20:52,836 --> 00:20:56,381
I will be firm but kind

190
00:20:56,423 --> 00:20:59,968
And all those children
Heaven bless them

191
00:21:00,010 --> 00:21:03,305
They will look up to me
And mind me

192
00:21:03,347 --> 00:21:06,808
With each step, I am more certain

193
00:21:06,850 --> 00:21:10,270
Everything will turn out fine

194
00:21:10,312 --> 00:21:13,524
I have confidence
The world can all be mine

195
00:21:13,565 --> 00:21:18,820
They'll have to agree
I have confidence in me

196
00:21:20,531 --> 00:21:23,659
I have confidence in sunshine

197
00:21:23,700 --> 00:21:26,870
I have confidence in rain

198
00:21:26,912 --> 00:21:29,998
I have confidence
That spring will come again

199
00:21:30,040 --> 00:21:33,502
Besides which you see
I have confidence in me

200
00:21:33,544 --> 00:21:36,755
Strength doesn't lie in numbers

201
00:21:36,797 --> 00:21:40,008
Strength doesn't lie in wealth

202
00:21:40,050 --> 00:21:43,595
Strength lies in nights
Of peaceful slumbers

203
00:21:43,637 --> 00:21:46,765
When you wake up, wake up
It's healthy

204
00:21:46,807 --> 00:21:49,810
All I trust I leave my heart to

205
00:21:50,060 --> 00:21:52,813
All I trust becomes my own

206
00:21:53,188 --> 00:21:57,401
I have confidence in confidence alone

207
00:22:12,583 --> 00:22:14,251
Oh, help.

208
00:22:26,430 --> 00:22:32,603
I have confidence in confidence alone

209
00:22:33,687 --> 00:22:38,525
Besides which you see
I have confidence

210
00:22:38,942 --> 00:22:45,782
in me

211
00:22:52,164 --> 00:22:54,583
Hello. Here I am.

212
00:22:57,419 --> 00:23:00,214
I'm from the convent.
I'm the new governess, Captain.

213
00:23:01,006 --> 00:23:03,884
And I'm the old butler, Fräulein.

214
00:23:06,136 --> 00:23:07,971
Well, how do you do?

215
00:23:18,565 --> 00:23:21,902
You'll wait here, please.

216
00:24:48,906 --> 00:24:53,535
In the future, remember certain rooms
in this house are not to be disturbed.

217
00:24:54,119 --> 00:24:55,829
Yes, Captain, sir.

218
00:25:03,670 --> 00:25:08,592
-Why do you stare at me that way?
-You don't look like a sea captain.

219
00:25:10,093 --> 00:25:13,305
I'm afraid you don't look
very much like a governess.

220
00:25:13,764 --> 00:25:15,307
-Turn around.
-What?

221
00:25:15,349 --> 00:25:16,683
Turn.

222
00:25:19,603 --> 00:25:20,938
Hat off.

223
00:25:23,941 --> 00:25:26,777
Put on another dress
before meeting the children.

224
00:25:26,818 --> 00:25:28,737
But I don't have another.

225
00:25:28,779 --> 00:25:31,740
When we enter the abbey,
our worldly clothes go to the poor.

226
00:25:31,782 --> 00:25:33,283
What about this one?

227
00:25:33,325 --> 00:25:35,285
The poor didn't want it.

228
00:25:36,537 --> 00:25:40,457
There wasn't time to make a new dress.
I can make clothes.

229
00:25:41,625 --> 00:25:44,127
I'll see that you get some material.

230
00:25:44,169 --> 00:25:45,963
Today, if possible.

231
00:25:46,797 --> 00:25:48,882
-Now, Fräulein...
-Maria.

232
00:25:48,924 --> 00:25:51,134
I don't know how much
the abbess told you.

233
00:25:51,176 --> 00:25:54,471
-Not much.
-You are the twelfth governess

234
00:25:54,513 --> 00:25:57,182
to look after my children
since their mother died.

235
00:25:57,224 --> 00:25:59,768
I trust you will be an improvement
on the last one.

236
00:25:59,810 --> 00:26:01,812
She stayed only two hours.

237
00:26:03,313 --> 00:26:05,941
What's wrong with the children, sir?

238
00:26:07,317 --> 00:26:11,029
Nothing is wrong with the children,
only the governesses.

239
00:26:11,947 --> 00:26:16,827
They could not maintain discipline,
without which the house cannot be run.

240
00:26:17,911 --> 00:26:19,663
Drill them in their studies.

241
00:26:19,705 --> 00:26:23,417
I will not permit them to dream
away their summer holidays.

242
00:26:23,750 --> 00:26:26,461
Each afternoon,
they march, breathing deeply.

243
00:26:26,503 --> 00:26:28,463
Bedtime is to be strictly observed.

244
00:26:28,505 --> 00:26:29,631
When do they play?

245
00:26:29,673 --> 00:26:33,886
You will see to it that they conduct
themselves with the utmost decorum.

246
00:26:33,927 --> 00:26:36,763
-I am placing you in command.
-Yes, sir.

247
00:27:57,594 --> 00:27:58,762
Now,

248
00:27:59,346 --> 00:28:02,266
this is your new governess,
Fräulein Maria.

249
00:28:03,934 --> 00:28:06,144
Give your name at your signal.

250
00:28:06,186 --> 00:28:10,107
Fräulein, listen carefully. Learn
their signals so you can call them.

251
00:28:11,650 --> 00:28:12,901
Liesl.

252
00:28:13,360 --> 00:28:14,778
Friedrich.

253
00:28:15,279 --> 00:28:16,572
Louisa.

254
00:28:17,114 --> 00:28:18,282
Kurt.

255
00:28:18,657 --> 00:28:19,867
Brigitta.

256
00:28:19,908 --> 00:28:21,118
Marta.

257
00:28:27,583 --> 00:28:28,792
Gretl.

258
00:28:33,547 --> 00:28:36,425
Now, let's see how well you listened.

259
00:28:37,217 --> 00:28:39,803
I won't need to whistle for them,
Reverend Captain.

260
00:28:39,845 --> 00:28:43,432
I mean, I'll use their names.
Such lovely names.

261
00:28:43,473 --> 00:28:46,894
Fräulein, this is a large house.
The grounds are extensive.

262
00:28:46,935 --> 00:28:49,771
And I will not have anyone shouting.

263
00:28:49,813 --> 00:28:51,773
You will take this, please.
Learn to use it.

264
00:28:51,815 --> 00:28:53,817
The children will help you.

265
00:28:55,569 --> 00:28:59,198
Now, when I want you,
this is what you will hear.

266
00:29:00,365 --> 00:29:02,409
Oh, no, sir. I'm sorry, sir!

267
00:29:03,118 --> 00:29:04,786
I could never answer to a whistle.

268
00:29:04,828 --> 00:29:07,623
Whistles are for animals,
not for children.

269
00:29:07,664 --> 00:29:09,708
And definitely not for me.

270
00:29:10,000 --> 00:29:12,211
It would be too humiliating.

271
00:29:13,587 --> 00:29:18,967
Fräulein, were you this much trouble
at the abbey?

272
00:29:19,009 --> 00:29:20,844
Oh, much more, sir.

273
00:29:31,313 --> 00:29:33,398
I don't know your signal.

274
00:29:34,274 --> 00:29:36,610
You may call me "Captain."

275
00:29:49,831 --> 00:29:51,291
At ease.

276
00:29:54,044 --> 00:29:55,838
Now that there's just us,

277
00:29:55,879 --> 00:30:00,050
would you please tell me all your
names again and how old you are.

278
00:30:00,551 --> 00:30:04,137
I'm Liesl. I'm 16 years old,
and I don't need a governess.

279
00:30:05,305 --> 00:30:08,725
I'm glad you told me, Liesl.
We'll just be good friends.

280
00:30:10,519 --> 00:30:13,772
I'm Friedrich. I'm 14.
I'm impossible.

281
00:30:14,565 --> 00:30:16,567
Really? Who told you that, Friedrich?

282
00:30:16,608 --> 00:30:19,570
Fräulein Josephine.
Four governesses ago.

283
00:30:20,487 --> 00:30:22,072
I'm Brigitta.

284
00:30:23,740 --> 00:30:27,077
You didn't tell me
how old you are, Louisa.

285
00:30:28,370 --> 00:30:30,581
I'm Brigitta. She's Louisa.

286
00:30:30,998 --> 00:30:33,750
She's 13 years old, and you're smart.

287
00:30:34,001 --> 00:30:38,088
I'm 10, and I think your dress
is the ugliest one I ever saw.

288
00:30:38,130 --> 00:30:40,841
-Brigitta, you shouldn't say that.
-Why not?

289
00:30:40,883 --> 00:30:43,468
-Don't you think it's ugly?
-Of course.

290
00:30:43,510 --> 00:30:45,971
But Fräulein Helga's was ugliest.

291
00:30:46,597 --> 00:30:49,349
I'm Kurt. I'm 11.
I'm incorrigible.

292
00:30:49,391 --> 00:30:52,269
-Congratulations.
-What's "incorrigible"?

293
00:30:52,769 --> 00:30:56,106
I think it means you want
to be treated like a boy.

294
00:30:58,859 --> 00:31:02,279
I'm Marta, and I'm going to be
seven on Tuesday.

295
00:31:02,321 --> 00:31:04,323
I'd like a pink parasol.

296
00:31:04,907 --> 00:31:06,992
Pink's my favorite color, too.

297
00:31:08,702 --> 00:31:10,329
Yes, you're Gretl.

298
00:31:10,787 --> 00:31:12,539
And you're five years old?

299
00:31:12,956 --> 00:31:14,958
My, you're practically a lady.

300
00:31:17,544 --> 00:31:21,215
I have to tell you a secret.
I've never been a governess.

301
00:31:22,049 --> 00:31:25,052
You don't know anything
about being a governess?

302
00:31:25,093 --> 00:31:27,346
Nothing. I'll need lots of advice.

303
00:31:27,387 --> 00:31:32,100
The best way to start is to tell
Father to mind his own business.

304
00:31:32,142 --> 00:31:34,102
Never come to dinner on time.

305
00:31:34,144 --> 00:31:36,480
Never eat your soup quietly.

306
00:31:37,147 --> 00:31:39,441
During dessert,
always blow your nose.

307
00:31:39,483 --> 00:31:42,444
Don't you believe a word they say,
Fräulein Maria.

308
00:31:42,486 --> 00:31:45,405
-Oh, why not?
-Because I like you.

309
00:31:46,657 --> 00:31:48,784
Children, outside for your walk.

310
00:31:48,825 --> 00:31:50,911
Father's orders. Hurry up.

311
00:31:50,953 --> 00:31:52,746
Quick, quick, quick.

312
00:31:52,788 --> 00:31:55,916
Fräulein Maria, I'm Frau Schmidt,
the housekeeper.

313
00:31:55,958 --> 00:31:57,125
How do you do.

314
00:31:57,167 --> 00:31:59,837
I'll show you to your room.
Follow me.

315
00:32:11,181 --> 00:32:12,933
Poor little dears.

316
00:32:25,654 --> 00:32:29,992
You're very lucky.
With Fräulein Helga it was a snake.

317
00:32:43,630 --> 00:32:44,923
Good evening.

318
00:32:46,633 --> 00:32:50,220
-Good evening, children.
-Good evening, Fräulein Maria.

319
00:32:57,394 --> 00:32:59,188
Enchanting little ritual.

320
00:32:59,229 --> 00:33:02,149
Something you learned at the abbey?

321
00:33:02,941 --> 00:33:04,318
No.

322
00:33:07,154 --> 00:33:08,405
Rheumatism.

323
00:33:18,332 --> 00:33:22,252
Excuse me, Captain.
Haven't we forgotten to thank the Lord?

324
00:33:29,593 --> 00:33:33,055
For what we receive,
may the Lord make us truly thankful.

325
00:33:33,096 --> 00:33:35,057
-Amen.
-Amen.

326
00:33:39,603 --> 00:33:41,396
I'd like to thank you all

327
00:33:41,438 --> 00:33:44,441
for the precious gift
you left in my pocket today.

328
00:33:48,195 --> 00:33:49,571
What gift?

329
00:33:53,116 --> 00:33:55,911
It's a secret between
the children and me.

330
00:33:55,953 --> 00:33:58,956
Then I suggest you keep it,
and let us eat.

331
00:33:59,581 --> 00:34:01,750
Knowing how nervous
I must have been,

332
00:34:01,792 --> 00:34:04,378
a stranger in a new household,

333
00:34:04,419 --> 00:34:07,714
knowing how important it was
for me to feel accepted,

334
00:34:07,756 --> 00:34:11,717
it was so kind and thoughtful of
you to make my first moments here

335
00:34:11,760 --> 00:34:13,971
so warm and happy

336
00:34:14,638 --> 00:34:16,139
and pleasant.

337
00:34:25,690 --> 00:34:28,277
-What is the matter, Marta?
-Nothing.

338
00:34:40,163 --> 00:34:45,168
Fräulein, is it to be at every meal
or merely at dinnertime

339
00:34:45,210 --> 00:34:49,797
that you intend leading us through
this rare and wonderful new world

340
00:34:50,132 --> 00:34:51,800
of indigestion?

341
00:34:53,802 --> 00:34:56,972
They're all right, Captain.
They're just happy.

342
00:35:15,032 --> 00:35:17,910
-Rolfe, good evening.
-Good evening, Franz.

343
00:35:17,951 --> 00:35:20,871
-I trust everything is under control?
-Yes, yes.

344
00:35:22,289 --> 00:35:24,875
-Are there any developments?
-Perhaps.

345
00:35:24,917 --> 00:35:27,377
-Is the Captain home?
-He's at dinner.

346
00:35:27,419 --> 00:35:29,755
-With the family?
-Yes.

347
00:35:30,088 --> 00:35:32,591
Give him this telegram at once.

348
00:35:32,633 --> 00:35:34,009
Certainly.

349
00:35:45,395 --> 00:35:47,397
A telegram for you, sir.

350
00:35:49,816 --> 00:35:52,152
Franz? Who delivered it?

351
00:35:52,194 --> 00:35:54,655
That young lad Rolfe, of course.

352
00:35:56,490 --> 00:35:58,617
Father, may I be excused?

353
00:35:59,117 --> 00:36:03,455
Children, in the morning
I shall be going to Vienna.

354
00:36:03,789 --> 00:36:06,542
Not again, Father!

355
00:36:10,212 --> 00:36:12,840
How long will you be gone this time?

356
00:36:12,881 --> 00:36:14,424
I'm not sure, Gretl.

357
00:36:14,466 --> 00:36:18,345
-To visit Baroness Schraeder again?
-Mind your own business!

358
00:36:19,012 --> 00:36:21,557
As a matter of fact, yes, Louisa.

359
00:36:22,349 --> 00:36:26,937
-Why can't we ever see the Baroness?
-Why would she want to see you?

360
00:36:26,979 --> 00:36:31,567
You are going to see the Baroness.
I'm bringing her back with me to visit.

361
00:36:33,193 --> 00:36:35,153
And Uncle Max.

362
00:36:35,195 --> 00:36:37,656
-Uncle Max!
-Uncle Max!

363
00:36:53,797 --> 00:36:55,090
Rolfe!

364
00:36:58,177 --> 00:36:59,553
Oh, Rolfe!

365
00:37:01,847 --> 00:37:04,975
-No, Liesl. We mustn't!
-Why not, silly?

366
00:37:05,017 --> 00:37:07,895
-I don't know...
-Isn't this why you're waiting?

367
00:37:07,936 --> 00:37:09,855
Yes, of course.

368
00:37:09,897 --> 00:37:12,900
-I've missed you, Liesl.
-You have? How much?

369
00:37:12,941 --> 00:37:17,112
I even thought of sending a telegram,
so I'd be able to deliver it here.

370
00:37:17,154 --> 00:37:21,241
Oh, that's a lovely thought!
Why don't you, right now?

371
00:37:21,283 --> 00:37:25,704
-But I'm here!
-Please, Rolfe. Send me a telegram.

372
00:37:25,746 --> 00:37:29,208
I'll start it for you. "Dear Liesl..."

373
00:37:29,833 --> 00:37:32,836
"Dear Liesl, I'd like to be able to tell you

374
00:37:32,878 --> 00:37:35,088
"how I feel about you. Stop.

375
00:37:36,048 --> 00:37:40,802
"Unfortunately, this wire
is already too expensive.

376
00:37:40,844 --> 00:37:42,471
"Sincerely, Rolfe."

377
00:37:42,513 --> 00:37:45,390
-"Sincerely"?
-Cordially.

378
00:37:45,432 --> 00:37:48,101
-"Cordially"?
-Affectionately?

379
00:37:50,437 --> 00:37:52,481
Will there be any reply?

380
00:37:53,774 --> 00:37:55,943
"Dear Rolfe. Stop.

381
00:37:56,860 --> 00:38:00,030
"Don't stop! Your Liesl."

382
00:38:01,740 --> 00:38:05,744
If only we didn't have to wait
for someone to send Father a telegram.

383
00:38:05,786 --> 00:38:08,539
How do I know when I'll see you again?

384
00:38:09,373 --> 00:38:11,083
Well, let's see...

385
00:38:13,502 --> 00:38:15,754
I could come here by mistake.

386
00:38:16,338 --> 00:38:21,009
With a telegram for Colonel Schneider!
He's here from Berlin staying with...

387
00:38:21,927 --> 00:38:25,222
No one knows he's here.
Don't tell your father.

388
00:38:25,472 --> 00:38:29,017
-Why not?
-Your father's so Austrian.

389
00:38:29,059 --> 00:38:30,352
We're all Austrian.

390
00:38:30,394 --> 00:38:34,940
Some think we ought to be German, and
they're very mad at those who don't.

391
00:38:34,982 --> 00:38:37,234
They're getting ready to...

392
00:38:38,485 --> 00:38:41,196
Let's hope your father
doesn't get into trouble.

393
00:38:41,238 --> 00:38:46,285
Don't worry. He's a big naval hero.
He was even decorated by the emperor.

394
00:38:46,326 --> 00:38:49,955
I don't worry about him.
I worry about his daughter.

395
00:38:49,997 --> 00:38:52,958
-Me? Why?
-Well, you're so...

396
00:38:53,959 --> 00:38:58,755
-You're such a baby!
-I'm 16. What's such a baby about that?

397
00:39:00,883 --> 00:39:04,678
You wait, little girl
On an empty stage

398
00:39:04,720 --> 00:39:07,556
For fate to turn the light on

399
00:39:08,682 --> 00:39:12,186
Your life, little girl
Is an empty page

400
00:39:12,227 --> 00:39:16,106
That men will want to write on

401
00:39:17,024 --> 00:39:22,279
To write on

402
00:39:23,447 --> 00:39:27,492
You are 16 going on 17

403
00:39:27,534 --> 00:39:31,038
Baby, it's time to think

404
00:39:31,538 --> 00:39:35,459
Better beware
Be canny and careful

405
00:39:35,501 --> 00:39:38,962
Baby, you're on the brink

406
00:39:39,463 --> 00:39:43,467
You are 16 going on 17

407
00:39:43,509 --> 00:39:47,429
Fellows will fall in line

408
00:39:47,471 --> 00:39:50,974
Eager young lads
And roués and cads

409
00:39:51,016 --> 00:39:55,437
Will offer you food and wine

410
00:39:55,479 --> 00:39:59,274
Totally unprepared are you

411
00:39:59,316 --> 00:40:02,778
To face a world of men

412
00:40:03,487 --> 00:40:07,157
Timid and shy and scared are you

413
00:40:07,199 --> 00:40:11,328
Of things beyond your ken

414
00:40:11,703 --> 00:40:15,791
You need someone older and wiser

415
00:40:15,832 --> 00:40:19,837
Telling you what to do

416
00:40:19,878 --> 00:40:23,799
I am 17 going on 18

417
00:40:23,841 --> 00:40:29,847
I'll take care of you

418
00:41:02,004 --> 00:41:05,674
I am 16 going on 17

419
00:41:05,716 --> 00:41:09,344
I know that I'm naive

420
00:41:09,386 --> 00:41:12,639
Fellows I meet
May tell me I'm sweet

421
00:41:12,681 --> 00:41:16,185
And willingly I believe

422
00:41:16,810 --> 00:41:20,522
I am 16 going on 17

423
00:41:20,564 --> 00:41:24,151
Innocent as a rose

424
00:41:24,193 --> 00:41:27,905
Bachelor dandies
Drinkers of brandies

425
00:41:27,946 --> 00:41:31,575
What do I know of those?

426
00:41:31,617 --> 00:41:35,204
Totally unprepared am I

427
00:41:35,245 --> 00:41:38,373
To face a world of men

428
00:41:39,249 --> 00:41:42,794
Timid and shy and scared am I

429
00:41:42,836 --> 00:41:46,507
Of things beyond my ken

430
00:41:46,965 --> 00:41:50,802
I need someone older and wiser

431
00:41:50,844 --> 00:41:54,515
Telling me what to do

432
00:41:54,556 --> 00:41:58,268
You are 17 going on 18

433
00:41:58,310 --> 00:42:03,649
I'll depend on you

434
00:43:57,137 --> 00:43:58,514
Come in.

435
00:43:59,556 --> 00:44:01,225
Frau Schmidt.

436
00:44:03,519 --> 00:44:05,521
For your new dresses.

437
00:44:05,562 --> 00:44:09,775
-The Captain had these sent from town.
-Oh, how lovely!

438
00:44:09,816 --> 00:44:13,695
These will make the prettiest clothes
I've ever had.

439
00:44:13,737 --> 00:44:17,282
Do you think he would
get me more material if I asked?

440
00:44:17,324 --> 00:44:21,161
-How many dresses do you need?
-Not for me, for the children.

441
00:44:21,203 --> 00:44:23,455
I want to make them some play clothes.

442
00:44:23,497 --> 00:44:27,084
The von Trapp children don't play.
They march.

443
00:44:27,459 --> 00:44:29,920
Surely you don't approve of that.

444
00:44:31,004 --> 00:44:33,549
Ever since the Captain lost his poor wife,

445
00:44:33,590 --> 00:44:36,677
he runs this house as if on one of his ships.

446
00:44:37,094 --> 00:44:38,637
Whistles, orders.

447
00:44:38,679 --> 00:44:40,931
No more music, no more laughing.

448
00:44:40,973 --> 00:44:44,476
Nothing that reminds him of her.
Even the children.

449
00:44:44,977 --> 00:44:46,895
But that's so wrong.

450
00:44:46,937 --> 00:44:48,689
Oh, well.

451
00:44:48,730 --> 00:44:52,609
How do you like your room?
There'll be new drapes at the windows.

452
00:44:52,651 --> 00:44:54,069
But these are fine.

453
00:44:54,111 --> 00:44:56,029
New ones have been ordered.

454
00:44:56,071 --> 00:44:59,533
-But I really don't need them.
-Good night, now.

455
00:44:59,575 --> 00:45:03,787
Frau Schmidt, if I asked
the Captain about the material...

456
00:45:03,829 --> 00:45:08,500
-He's leaving in the morning.
-Of course. How long will he be gone?

457
00:45:08,917 --> 00:45:13,505
It depends. The last time he visited
the Baroness, he stayed for a month.

458
00:45:14,548 --> 00:45:19,136
I shouldn't be saying this to you.
I don't know you that well.

459
00:45:19,469 --> 00:45:22,514
But if you ask me,
the Captain's thinking seriously

460
00:45:22,556 --> 00:45:25,058
of marrying her before summer's over.

461
00:45:25,100 --> 00:45:28,353
Wonderful! The children will
have a mother again.

462
00:45:29,646 --> 00:45:31,148
Yes.

463
00:45:31,190 --> 00:45:33,233
Well, good night.

464
00:45:33,275 --> 00:45:34,735
Good night.

465
00:45:53,086 --> 00:45:56,131
Dear Father, now I know
why you sent me here.

466
00:45:56,173 --> 00:45:59,134
To help these children
prepare for a new mother.

467
00:45:59,176 --> 00:46:02,763
And I pray this will become
a happy family in Thy sight.

468
00:46:02,804 --> 00:46:06,099
God bless the Captain.
God bless Liesl and Friedrich.

469
00:46:06,141 --> 00:46:10,479
God bless Louisa, Brigitta,
Marta and little Gretl.

470
00:46:10,521 --> 00:46:13,524
And I forgot the other boy.
What's his name?

471
00:46:15,108 --> 00:46:17,027
Well, God bless what's-his-name.

472
00:46:17,069 --> 00:46:21,406
God bless the Reverend Mother
and Sister Margaretta

473
00:46:21,448 --> 00:46:23,325
and everybody at the abbey.

474
00:46:23,367 --> 00:46:25,911
And now, dear God, about Liesl.

475
00:46:26,411 --> 00:46:28,497
Help her know that I'm her friend

476
00:46:28,539 --> 00:46:31,667
and help her tell me
what she's been up to.

477
00:46:31,708 --> 00:46:33,293
Are you going to tell on me?

478
00:46:33,335 --> 00:46:36,755
Help me to be understanding
so I may guide her footsteps.

479
00:46:36,797 --> 00:46:39,800
In the name of the Father,
the Son and the Holy Ghost.

480
00:46:39,842 --> 00:46:42,970
I was out walking
and somebody locked the doors early.

481
00:46:43,011 --> 00:46:47,140
I didn't want to wake everybody,
so when I saw your window open...

482
00:46:48,350 --> 00:46:51,436
You're not going to tell Father, are you?

483
00:46:57,526 --> 00:46:59,152
How did you climb up?

484
00:46:59,194 --> 00:47:02,531
It's how we always got in
to play tricks on the governess.

485
00:47:02,573 --> 00:47:06,535
Louisa can make it with
a whole jar of spiders in her hand.

486
00:47:06,577 --> 00:47:08,161
Spiders?

487
00:47:10,414 --> 00:47:14,751
Liesl, were you out walking all by yourself?

488
00:47:22,092 --> 00:47:26,138
If we wash that dress tonight,
nobody would notice it tomorrow.

489
00:47:26,471 --> 00:47:28,390
You could put this on.

490
00:47:29,933 --> 00:47:32,811
Take your dress
and put it to soak in the bathtub.

491
00:47:32,853 --> 00:47:36,523
Come back here and sit on the bed,
and we'll have a talk.

492
00:47:37,691 --> 00:47:40,944
I told you today I didn't need a governess.

493
00:47:40,986 --> 00:47:43,113
Well, maybe I do.

494
00:48:13,519 --> 00:48:16,063
Gretl, are you scared?

495
00:48:19,525 --> 00:48:22,069
You're not frightened of a storm, are you?

496
00:48:22,110 --> 00:48:24,613
You just stay right here with me.

497
00:48:25,572 --> 00:48:29,785
-Where are the others?
-They're asleep. They're not scared.

498
00:48:34,248 --> 00:48:36,083
Oh, no? Look.

499
00:48:37,668 --> 00:48:39,753
All right, up here on the bed.

500
00:48:39,795 --> 00:48:42,548
-Really?
-Well, just this once. Come on.

501
00:48:43,590 --> 00:48:47,970
